WEBVTT

00:06.316 --> 00:15.877
[ Wolf howling,
animals calling ]

00:15.912 --> 00:18.466
Narrator:
Previously on "Mountain Men"...

00:18.501 --> 00:20.503
[ Growling ]...in the depths of winter...

00:20.537 --> 00:22.712
This is real close
to our house.

00:22.746 --> 00:24.058
...the wolves are circling...

00:24.093 --> 00:27.613
Tom: Chances are they'll
be back to this site.

00:27.648 --> 00:30.961
Narrator: ...from Montana
to Alaska.

00:30.996 --> 00:34.275
One, two, three,
four, five.

00:34.310 --> 00:35.794
There is a lot
of wolves here.

00:35.828 --> 00:37.037
That's ideal.

00:37.071 --> 00:39.384
If I find enough kills,
I can also be catching

00:39.418 --> 00:41.627
a different kind of fur.

00:41.662 --> 00:46.011
Narrator: And Morgan fights the
deep freeze to break new ground.

00:46.046 --> 00:48.427
Morgan:
I don't know about this.

00:48.462 --> 00:50.257
I think that's just solid ice

00:50.291 --> 00:52.845
all the way down
to the old snow layer.

00:52.880 --> 00:54.709
I've wasted a bunch of time.

00:54.744 --> 01:04.788
♪♪

01:04.788 --> 01:15.144
♪♪

01:17.594 --> 01:20.942
Narrator: Alaskan winters are
some of the harshest on Earth,

01:20.977 --> 01:22.737
and when the cold sets in,

01:22.772 --> 01:26.845
the competition for food
and territory heats up.

01:26.879 --> 01:31.021
In Two Rivers, where the wolf
population is on the rise,

01:31.056 --> 01:33.507
the battle to stay on top
of the food chain

01:33.541 --> 01:38.270
offers Marty Meierotto
an unexpected break.

01:38.305 --> 01:39.892
Marty: I saw the wolf tracks.

01:39.927 --> 01:41.653
Having the opportunity,
I just thought,

01:41.687 --> 01:43.241
"Yeah, I should take it."

01:43.275 --> 01:45.553
Narrator: He's 200 feet
above the tree line

01:45.588 --> 01:47.348
hunting for a wolf kill

01:47.383 --> 01:50.834
because where there's prey,
there's good trapping.

01:50.869 --> 01:52.733
Marty: So if I find a kill,

01:52.767 --> 01:55.529
obviously,
I can probably catch wolves,

01:55.563 --> 01:58.152
but there's also marten
come to kills,

01:58.187 --> 02:01.017
and wolverine are a sucker
for big baits like that.

02:01.051 --> 02:04.779
So you have a opportunity
to catch a decent amount of fur.

02:04.814 --> 02:07.541
Narrator: Marty has returned
to Two Rivers to regroup

02:07.575 --> 02:09.612
after a disastrous beginning.

02:09.646 --> 02:13.581
Marty: It's been
a pretty tough season.

02:13.616 --> 02:19.346
You feel the pressure,
the stress of being behind.

02:19.380 --> 02:21.969
Is this whole season
going to be a bust?

02:22.003 --> 02:24.178
How is it all going
to shake out?

02:24.213 --> 02:25.662
I got a lot riding on this,

02:25.697 --> 02:29.735
so I'm really hoping
to get something.

02:29.770 --> 02:31.220
Narrator: Now with
just eight weeks left

02:31.254 --> 02:32.911
to earn his money for the year,

02:32.945 --> 02:35.224
he needs to make up
for lost time.

03:03.321 --> 03:12.916
♪♪

03:23.375 --> 03:28.898
Well, it looks like they
killed him a day or two back.

03:28.932 --> 03:31.349
They usually clean up
caribou pretty fast

03:31.383 --> 03:34.248
because they're smaller.

03:34.283 --> 03:36.319
It looks like a cow.

03:36.354 --> 03:38.597
I can't see any horn
pedestals there.

03:38.632 --> 03:40.392
There's not much left.

03:40.427 --> 03:42.118
It's a big pack,
so they probably

03:42.152 --> 03:45.121
gobbled him up pretty fast.

03:45.155 --> 03:48.849
It ain't a pretty thing,
but that's nature.

03:48.883 --> 03:50.160
Narrator: A wolf pack
will move on

03:50.195 --> 03:52.542
once it strips
a carcass to the bones,

03:52.577 --> 03:54.889
but scavengers arrive
like a second wave

03:54.924 --> 03:56.374
to pick up the scraps,

03:56.408 --> 03:59.584
and that's exactly what Marty
is counting on to get ahead.

03:59.618 --> 04:03.001
Marty: There's marten tracks,
wolverine sign.

04:03.035 --> 04:04.244
Even though there's
not much left,

04:04.278 --> 04:06.004
a wolverine will eat
all those bones.

04:06.038 --> 04:09.249
That's food for them, so if
there's any wolverine around,

04:09.283 --> 04:10.974
he's going to come and eat that.

04:11.009 --> 04:12.424
I'm going to go to that far bank

04:12.459 --> 04:15.358
and make a 330 cubby
for wolverine.

04:15.393 --> 04:18.188
♪♪

04:18.223 --> 04:21.191
I think I'm going to use the
base of this spruce right here.

04:21.226 --> 04:23.470
Narrator: A cubby set is
designed to lure the animal

04:23.504 --> 04:26.473
one way into
a camouflaged steel trap.

04:26.507 --> 04:31.409
Marty: I'll just lay sticks
or branches up in kind of a "V"

04:31.443 --> 04:34.135
so that he can't
come in from the side,

04:34.170 --> 04:36.897
and then I got
a bag of fish heads.

04:36.931 --> 04:39.727
Wolverine will come
to any big smell.

04:39.762 --> 04:43.041
So, basically, you've got
something they want,

04:43.075 --> 04:44.939
and there's only one way
to get to it.

04:44.974 --> 04:48.564
I'm going to take my 330.

04:48.598 --> 04:53.189
I'm going to set it up
like that.

04:53.223 --> 04:56.434
Okay, so that's the cubby set,

04:56.468 --> 04:57.918
and then I'm just going
to bump over there

04:57.952 --> 05:01.680
and make a pole set for marten
on either side of the cubby.

05:01.715 --> 05:04.580
Narrator: The price of marten is
at an all-time low this season,

05:04.614 --> 05:06.996
but Marty needs
every last dollar

05:07.030 --> 05:08.653
if he's going to break even.

05:08.687 --> 05:10.689
There's going to be
some marten showing up,

05:10.724 --> 05:13.313
so I might as well put
in another set and catch them.

05:16.937 --> 05:25.048
♪♪

05:25.083 --> 05:31.227
Narrator: In Alaska, 200 miles
from the Arctic Circle,

05:31.261 --> 05:36.577
the Great Alaska Range is known
as the Land of Eternal Winter.

05:36.612 --> 05:39.994
It gets more than 100 inches
of snowfall every year.

05:42.238 --> 05:44.378
And for five long months,

05:44.413 --> 05:46.656
deep drifts
and snowbanks transform

05:46.691 --> 05:48.969
the landscape
into a treacherous gauntlet

05:49.003 --> 05:54.043
that's difficult to navigate
without the proper tools.

05:54.077 --> 05:56.286
Morgan: I've been using
snowshoes for everything

05:56.321 --> 05:57.736
for the last few years.

05:57.771 --> 06:01.671
They're good for pulling sleds
or heavy loads or working

06:01.706 --> 06:04.433
with a chain saw
or something in the snow.

06:04.467 --> 06:06.676
Narrator: Snowshoes are
an ancient Native American

06:06.711 --> 06:09.783
invention that Morgan Beasley
has come to rely on to navigate

06:09.817 --> 06:12.820
the wild terrain
around his homestead.

06:12.855 --> 06:16.134
They're sturdy,
but they're not built for speed.

06:16.168 --> 06:18.723
And with his territory
expanding,

06:18.757 --> 06:21.208
he needs a new way
to get around.

06:21.242 --> 06:22.934
All right, I'm going
to go try to

06:22.968 --> 06:24.763
split some planks
off for skis.

06:24.798 --> 06:27.421
Skis are way more efficient,
especially if you're traveling

06:27.456 --> 06:29.492
the same route
over and over again

06:29.527 --> 06:32.737
like we are with this trap line.

06:32.771 --> 06:35.774
I've never made skis before,
so if I can make skis

06:35.809 --> 06:39.778
that I can get around on,
I'm going to be thrilled.

06:39.813 --> 06:43.368
I've been keeping my eyes peeled
for a really good spruce

06:43.403 --> 06:45.784
to make skis out of,

06:45.819 --> 06:48.718
and I have a tree picked out
that has about the straightest,

06:48.753 --> 06:52.998
clearest grain of anything
on the property.

06:53.033 --> 06:56.968
If it's got nice, straight grain
that's all parallel to itself

06:57.002 --> 06:59.488
and parallel to the ski,
it'll bend a little better,

06:59.522 --> 07:01.524
and it'll resist breaking.

07:01.559 --> 07:02.905
Narrator: Cutting quality skis

07:02.939 --> 07:05.217
requires a tree
that's naturally straight.

07:05.252 --> 07:08.289
A uniform grain will give
the ski more flexibility

07:08.324 --> 07:11.396
and allow it to glide
easily over the snow.

07:11.431 --> 07:13.502
Is that the right tree, buddy?
Yeah, I know.

07:13.536 --> 07:15.642
It's about the straightest,
nicest tree around.

07:15.676 --> 07:17.471
There's this kind of whole side

07:17.506 --> 07:19.542
that doesn't really have
any knots,

07:19.577 --> 07:21.924
and that's going to make it
split off a lot easier.

07:21.958 --> 07:23.684
I'm just going to try to fall it
with the wind,

07:23.719 --> 07:26.687
which should be the most
straightforward way to go.

07:26.722 --> 07:28.793
♪♪

07:28.827 --> 07:31.278
[ Chainsaw motor revs ]

07:31.312 --> 07:43.152
♪♪

07:43.186 --> 07:45.637
Timber!

07:45.672 --> 07:50.124
♪♪

07:50.159 --> 07:53.611
Excellent, right where
I wanted it.

07:53.645 --> 07:57.891
I'm going to rip a line
down through it, so that way,

07:57.925 --> 08:00.721
it can create an edge
for two different planks

08:00.756 --> 08:03.621
because I need two skis,
obviously.

08:03.655 --> 08:05.485
Narrator: Ripping the board
separates the wood

08:05.519 --> 08:06.969
along the natural grain,

08:07.003 --> 08:10.006
allowing for a straighter split
than a saw cut.

08:10.041 --> 08:15.046
Morgan: Try to establish
the split about where I want it.

08:15.080 --> 08:16.461
[ Groans ]

08:16.496 --> 08:17.876
That wasn't good.

08:17.911 --> 08:23.537
I've never really tried
to split off planks like this.

08:23.572 --> 08:26.126
Narrator: The planks need to be
at least 5 1/2 feet long

08:26.160 --> 08:31.649
and 2 inches thick throughout
in order to shape into skis.

08:31.683 --> 08:35.756
Morgan: Here.

08:35.791 --> 08:37.689
Narrator: Wood splitting wedges
apply pressure

08:37.724 --> 08:40.623
to help the planks split evenly.

08:40.658 --> 08:43.799
Morgan: I'll get this wedge
in here and see what I can do.

08:43.833 --> 08:47.043
A wedge will fit right into
where the ax had been,

08:47.078 --> 08:48.942
and I can start to drive
that wedge,

08:48.976 --> 08:51.013
and it'll start to pry
that wood apart.

08:51.047 --> 08:53.567
I don't want to be
too aggressive right away

08:53.602 --> 08:56.950
because I might just split
a chunk off like I did up here.

09:01.506 --> 09:06.994
If I let this set for a second,
it'll kind of keep

09:07.029 --> 09:09.479
adjusting to its new reality.

09:12.897 --> 09:14.588
And while that's
kind of setting here,

09:14.623 --> 09:16.038
maybe I'll start the other one.

09:16.072 --> 09:19.075
The wood is under tension,
but if you leave it there

09:19.110 --> 09:20.525
for a minute or two, hopefully,

09:20.560 --> 09:23.355
it'll slowly start
to split itself.

09:23.390 --> 09:26.566
♪♪

09:26.600 --> 09:30.190
I'll let that one soak,
move back to the other side.

09:30.224 --> 09:35.575
♪♪

09:35.609 --> 09:37.680
Switch back to this side now.

09:37.715 --> 09:45.654
♪♪

09:45.688 --> 09:47.103
It's kind of nerve-wracking.

09:47.138 --> 09:49.312
It's a lot of work, and if it
doesn't split off clean,

09:49.347 --> 09:52.143
kind of all wasted.

09:52.177 --> 09:56.872
I'm going to try to get this
left-hand-side one off first.

09:56.906 --> 10:01.428
There. Wow.

10:01.462 --> 10:03.223
Nice.

10:03.257 --> 10:07.296
Here it goes.

10:07.330 --> 10:10.506
Okay.
I think I can work with this.

10:10.540 --> 10:14.717
♪♪

10:14.752 --> 10:17.064
Oh, yeah.
Cool.

10:17.099 --> 10:19.860
And now it's just going to take
a lot of careful shaping

10:19.895 --> 10:22.345
to get these kind of to where
they're thin enough

10:22.380 --> 10:26.108
to bend into skis.

10:26.142 --> 10:28.628
Come on, Rufus.

10:28.662 --> 10:38.672
♪♪

10:38.707 --> 10:42.952
Narrator: This winter, Montana
is under siege by predators,

10:42.987 --> 10:44.264
and one of the deadliest,

10:44.298 --> 10:47.819
the gray wolf,
is on the rise.

10:47.854 --> 10:52.375
An estimated 40 packs
are thriving across the state,

10:52.410 --> 10:53.998
including the Yaak Valley

10:54.032 --> 10:56.276
where Tom Oar recently
discovered signs

10:56.310 --> 10:59.728
of a dangerous incursion
on his property.

10:59.762 --> 11:02.351
Tom: We got more wolves
in this part of the state

11:02.385 --> 11:03.697
than probably any other,

11:03.732 --> 11:08.702
and I've got the right
to hunt them and trap them.

11:08.737 --> 11:09.910
I love wolves.

11:09.945 --> 11:12.085
You know, I don't want
to kill all the wolves,

11:12.119 --> 11:15.157
but still, wolves kill anything

11:15.191 --> 11:18.022
that would be
in competition with them,

11:18.056 --> 11:21.473
and if they caught my dog
out in the woods,

11:21.508 --> 11:24.580
they'd surely kill her
and eat her.

11:24.614 --> 11:27.445
Narrator: Today, Tom is
on predator patrol,

11:27.479 --> 11:29.309
returning to the site
of the wolf kill

11:29.343 --> 11:31.760
where he's laid two traps.

11:31.794 --> 11:35.729
Tom: I've been checking them
every day, but nothing yet.

11:35.764 --> 11:38.214
Narrator: But the foot of
fresh snow that fell overnight

11:38.249 --> 11:44.117
may have foiled his defenses.

11:44.151 --> 11:46.982
Tom: All of a sudden,
we just got all this snowfall.

11:47.016 --> 11:49.432
I'll check them first, make sure
that we don't have anything,

11:49.467 --> 11:51.711
but when the snow
comes like this,

11:51.745 --> 11:54.058
the wolf's foot probably
can't even get down

11:54.092 --> 11:57.544
to where the trap is.

11:57.578 --> 12:00.374
I've got nothing.

12:00.409 --> 12:05.725
I don't see any sign of any
wolf track or any sign at all.

12:05.759 --> 12:08.348
I don't even see any sign
of the kill.

12:08.382 --> 12:09.936
It's all covered up.

12:09.970 --> 12:12.145
All right. Well...

12:12.179 --> 12:15.286
Narrator: With the traps buried
too deep to catch anything,

12:15.320 --> 12:17.633
Tom decides to pull them,

12:17.667 --> 12:20.843
leaving him vulnerable
if the wolves return.

12:20.878 --> 12:24.398
Seems real senseless for me to
take that snowmobile and drive

12:24.433 --> 12:26.815
to them wolf traps
every day to check them

12:26.849 --> 12:29.714
with all this snow
on top of the traps.

12:31.820 --> 12:34.650
Might be hard to even find them.

12:34.684 --> 12:42.900
♪♪

12:42.934 --> 12:44.833
Here, I think this
is where it was.

12:44.867 --> 12:49.665
This is my dent, I think,
that I made when I put this in.

12:49.699 --> 12:53.048
Where I set my trap,
there was still a little sign

12:53.082 --> 12:54.946
that there had been
a trail there,

12:54.981 --> 13:00.055
but these traps, they got to be
two foot underneath the snow.

13:00.089 --> 13:11.860
♪♪

13:11.894 --> 13:15.415
I think Sean's trap
is just right there.

13:15.449 --> 13:18.936
Where Sean set his trap
is covered with snow.

13:18.970 --> 13:21.870
It makes it almost
impossible to find.

13:21.904 --> 13:24.113
It's a lot of snow.

13:24.148 --> 13:28.531
Hell, even a grizzly
couldn't walk over this.

13:28.566 --> 13:31.258
I sure think this is the spot.

13:31.293 --> 13:33.191
We're just not deep enough.

13:36.919 --> 13:38.852
It's just deep snow.

13:38.887 --> 13:42.407
Really makes it hard
to get around in,

13:42.442 --> 13:44.754
makes everything harder to do.

13:46.826 --> 13:51.658
Well, back to the sled, I guess.

13:51.692 --> 13:58.320
♪♪

13:58.354 --> 14:08.364
♪♪

14:08.399 --> 14:16.062
[ Engine sputtering ]

14:16.096 --> 14:22.620
I don't know
what the deal is here.

14:22.654 --> 14:24.449
[ SputteriDamn.nti

14:24.484 --> 14:30.455
Snowmobiles, to a trapper,
are pretty important.

14:30.490 --> 14:36.254
But when them suckers
don't work, they're a real drag.

14:36.289 --> 14:39.223
I'll skin your beavers for you,
and I'll do it real good,

14:39.257 --> 14:42.226
but I don't know anything
about carburetors

14:42.260 --> 14:47.024
or generators
or none of that stuff.

14:47.058 --> 14:49.474
[ Sighs ]

14:49.509 --> 14:54.721
♪♪

14:54.755 --> 14:57.103
Going to pull these spark plugs.

14:57.137 --> 15:00.451
Let me put another set in here.

15:00.485 --> 15:04.455
I got to carry two sets with me
just in case this happens.

15:04.489 --> 15:07.527
Maybe this will work.

15:07.561 --> 15:10.323
Taking the old plugs out,
and I put new plugs in it,

15:10.357 --> 15:12.946
that's about all I know about.

15:12.981 --> 15:20.091
♪♪

15:20.126 --> 15:22.680
Well, we'll give her
another try.

15:22.714 --> 15:24.578
See if this will work.

15:26.787 --> 15:28.824
Come on, baby.
You can do it.

15:28.858 --> 15:35.865
[ Engine sputters ]

15:35.900 --> 15:37.729
Well, maybe it can't.

15:37.764 --> 15:39.248
[ Chuckles ]

15:39.283 --> 15:41.837
Damn you, huh.

15:41.871 --> 15:44.667
[ Sighs ]

15:44.702 --> 15:47.808
Well, I don't know
what else I can do.

15:49.949 --> 15:52.813
I'll just have to walk home,
I guess.

15:52.848 --> 15:55.057
Narrator: Tom is just
one mile from home,

15:55.092 --> 15:57.749
but with knees plagued
by old rodeo injuries,

15:57.784 --> 15:58.992
the deep snow conditions

15:59.027 --> 16:02.858
will make navigating
the distance more arduous.

16:02.892 --> 16:05.136
Tom: At least I got snow shoes.

16:05.171 --> 16:09.692
I'm lucky I brought them
with today, I'll tell you.

16:09.727 --> 16:12.592
I'm headed for the house.

16:12.626 --> 16:16.734
All right.
Here we go.

16:16.768 --> 16:19.495
It's always good when you got
deep snow like this

16:19.530 --> 16:24.431
just to have them snowshoes
with you just in case.

16:29.367 --> 16:36.616
♪♪

16:36.650 --> 16:39.860
Narrator: The Ozark Mountains
cover 47,000 square miles

16:39.895 --> 16:41.793
of the South Central U.S.,

16:41.828 --> 16:45.383
from St. Louis
to the Arkansas River.

16:45.418 --> 16:47.661
It's an area known
for its rugged mountains

16:47.696 --> 16:49.767
and forested highlands.

16:49.801 --> 16:53.978
These peaks are home to more
than 200,000 feral hogs,

16:54.013 --> 16:57.809
but to feed his family,
Jason Hawk needs just one.

16:57.844 --> 17:00.950
Me and Mary had
built a hog trap.

17:00.985 --> 17:04.161
Didn't take but a couple hours
for a hog to get into it,

17:04.195 --> 17:06.197
but he also got out of it.

17:06.232 --> 17:08.441
Once a hog has been
spooked out of a trap,

17:08.475 --> 17:10.270
the likelihood of them
being back

17:10.305 --> 17:13.101
sure not going to be
in the next couple weeks.

17:13.135 --> 17:15.068
Narrator: The Hawks only
have enough meat to last

17:15.103 --> 17:17.277
two more days,
and after yesterday's

17:17.312 --> 17:19.314
failed attempt
to improvise a trap,

17:19.348 --> 17:23.697
Jason is out
on an old-fashioned hog hunt.

17:23.732 --> 17:27.080
Jason: Best place to start
is just where he got out.

17:27.115 --> 17:29.013
I might not be able
to find this hog,

17:29.048 --> 17:32.568
but he'll probably lead me
to the rest of the troop.

17:32.603 --> 17:34.605
He just rooted in here
till he wound up

17:34.639 --> 17:36.814
pulling the two portions
of the fence apart,

17:36.848 --> 17:39.299
decided to make a jailbreak.

17:39.334 --> 17:42.095
What I'm going to be looking for
more than anything is an area

17:42.130 --> 17:44.028
that the leaves
have been pushed down.

17:44.063 --> 17:45.926
The other thing I'm really
going to be looking for

17:45.961 --> 17:49.447
is directionality
through the leaves.

17:49.482 --> 17:52.036
Doesn't seem like much,
but as you move a little bit,

17:52.071 --> 17:55.453
you notice the leaves build up
in front, not behind.

17:55.488 --> 18:00.734
♪♪

18:00.769 --> 18:02.771
Here we go.

18:02.805 --> 18:04.945
That'll be the indicator here.

18:04.980 --> 18:09.053
Cut up this way.

18:09.088 --> 18:12.263
Right there where the shadow
of that tree limb is

18:12.298 --> 18:15.128
is a little trail
that took off here to the left.

18:15.163 --> 18:17.682
I'm going to see if I can find
some feral hogs.

18:17.717 --> 18:20.271
I need to get some meat
and put it on the table.

18:20.306 --> 18:22.204
I got a family depending on me.

18:22.239 --> 18:34.768
♪♪

18:34.803 --> 18:37.461
Narrator:
Outside Two Rivers, Alaska,

18:37.495 --> 18:39.497
a wolf pack moving
through the area

18:39.532 --> 18:42.190
is leaving a trail
of carnage in its wake.

19:04.143 --> 19:13.428
♪♪

19:15.119 --> 19:22.091
♪♪

19:22.126 --> 19:24.715
All right, we can kind of see
the scene of the crime here.

19:24.749 --> 19:27.545
We'll go take a look at it.

19:27.580 --> 19:30.134
Narrator: The blood and bones
that remain are a beacon

19:30.169 --> 19:32.723
to the local game animals
that Marty relies on

19:32.757 --> 19:35.829
to make his living.

19:35.864 --> 19:40.179
Marty: Well, here's the kill.
This is where it come down.

19:40.213 --> 19:41.525
Looks like a calf.

19:41.559 --> 19:43.699
It just pulled him
down, youngster.

19:43.734 --> 19:45.391
I wonder what the cow did.

19:45.425 --> 19:48.428
You know, a cow could be dead
around here somewhere, too.

19:48.463 --> 19:50.534
Usually, if they get the calf,

19:50.568 --> 19:52.639
lots of times,
they get the cow, too,

19:52.674 --> 19:55.608
because the cow kind of tries
to protect the calf.

19:55.642 --> 19:59.163
♪♪

19:59.198 --> 20:05.238
So you can kind of see here
the moose was stumbling along,

20:05.273 --> 20:07.413
and the wolves were
pulling her down,

20:07.447 --> 20:10.830
and she was really struggling,
and you could see,

20:10.864 --> 20:13.867
actually, where a wolf
was just dragging.

20:13.902 --> 20:15.317
It isn't an instant thing.

20:15.352 --> 20:17.940
They chase her.
They wear her down.

20:17.975 --> 20:20.253
Then they can start
taking chunks.

20:20.288 --> 20:22.082
When she gets weakened
to a point

20:22.117 --> 20:24.188
where they can actually
warm on top of her,

20:24.223 --> 20:28.779
then they just pile on
and slowly drag her down,

20:28.813 --> 20:32.265
and then she ends up
looking like that over there.

20:32.300 --> 20:34.750
She made it quite a ways,

20:34.785 --> 20:37.512
100, 150 yards with wolves
hanging on your back.

20:37.546 --> 20:39.134
That's pretty good.

20:39.168 --> 20:41.723
Narrator: Discovering two
kill sites on the same day

20:41.757 --> 20:44.622
just 10 miles apart
is a sign of Alaska's

20:44.657 --> 20:46.279
healthy wolf population,

20:46.314 --> 20:49.455
which has been rising steadily
over the last five years.

20:49.489 --> 20:52.285
But in nature,
balance is everything.

20:52.320 --> 20:54.632
Marty: There is a lot
of wolves up here,

20:54.667 --> 20:56.531
and if you have to many wolves,

20:56.565 --> 20:58.084
they eat themselves
out of house and home,

20:58.118 --> 20:59.879
and pretty soon,
you don't have any wolves.

20:59.913 --> 21:02.468
You don't have any moose
or caribou either.

21:02.502 --> 21:04.573
Narrator: Wolves have few
natural predators,

21:04.608 --> 21:06.920
and trappers like Marty
can be vital

21:06.955 --> 21:10.096
in keeping the population
at sustainable levels.

21:10.130 --> 21:12.857
Marty: If you can manage them,
if you can take a few wolves

21:12.892 --> 21:14.549
and kind of balance that,

21:14.583 --> 21:16.965
it'll actually help
the wolf population out

21:16.999 --> 21:19.001
because they're not going
to eat up everything

21:19.036 --> 21:21.625
and then starve themselves.

21:21.659 --> 21:23.316
Narrator: Culling the pack
could protect both

21:23.351 --> 21:26.285
the wildlife
and Marty's livelihood.

21:26.319 --> 21:29.771
A single pelt can fetch
more than $500,

21:29.805 --> 21:33.015
enough to make a dent
in his season's debt.

21:33.050 --> 21:35.363
Marty: It looks like
they fed last night,

21:35.397 --> 21:37.088
but there's still
quite a bit here,

21:37.123 --> 21:40.333
so they should come back.

21:40.368 --> 21:44.061
What I think I'll do,
I'll just move along that bank,

21:44.095 --> 21:46.684
and I'll set a snare
in each wolf trail.

21:46.719 --> 21:48.893
One there.

21:48.928 --> 21:50.930
There's one there.

21:50.964 --> 21:54.105
May go up the bank there,
and then one over there.

21:54.140 --> 21:57.454
That's four, four trails.

21:57.488 --> 22:12.158
♪♪

22:12.192 --> 22:14.263
Marty: I try to take my time.
Don't rush it.

22:14.298 --> 22:15.955
Just look around.

22:15.989 --> 22:18.233
You just got to try and sit
there and scratch your head

22:18.267 --> 22:19.993
and try to think
like a wolf, you know.

22:20.028 --> 22:22.341
If I was a wolf,
where would I go?

22:22.375 --> 22:26.862
♪♪

22:26.897 --> 22:29.865
Here's a wolf bed here.

22:29.900 --> 22:32.799
After they feed,
they lay around.

22:32.834 --> 22:35.975
They're kind of -- Some people
call it a meat drunk,

22:36.009 --> 22:37.459
where they just
gorge themselves,

22:37.494 --> 22:41.152
and then they got
to sleep it off.

22:41.187 --> 22:43.845
There's a bunch of
blood over there.

22:43.879 --> 22:46.157
I'd better go check that out.

22:46.192 --> 22:49.333
That's just where
a wolf was laying there.

22:49.368 --> 22:51.887
You know, the wolf
could've got hurt.

22:51.922 --> 22:54.614
A moose is fighting
for its life.

22:54.649 --> 22:58.825
It's going to kick.

22:58.860 --> 23:02.450
That looks like a wolf trail
coming down there.

23:02.484 --> 23:04.037
The wolves tell you
where to set.

23:04.072 --> 23:06.764
If they have a trail,
you set in the trail.

23:06.799 --> 23:08.145
Wolves, they're just
like people.

23:08.179 --> 23:09.422
They're lazy.

23:09.457 --> 23:10.872
All things being equal,
they'll walk down a trial

23:10.906 --> 23:13.978
as opposed to walking
through powder snow.

23:14.013 --> 23:16.636
Okay. I'm going
to hang one right here.

23:16.671 --> 23:19.467
I use good, stiff wire
to hold the snare in place

23:19.501 --> 23:22.504
where I want it to be,
so when the wolf goes into it,

23:22.539 --> 23:24.368
the snare goes around his neck,

23:24.403 --> 23:27.647
and it'll tighten,
but it won't ever loosen.

23:27.682 --> 23:30.270
Yeah, there we go.
That's the wolf trail.

23:30.305 --> 23:33.032
He'll come through here
on his way, and hopefully,

23:33.066 --> 23:35.241
my tracks won't
screw him up too bad,

23:35.275 --> 23:37.450
and he'll be in the snare
before he realizes

23:37.485 --> 23:39.625
that I was walking here.

23:39.659 --> 23:41.247
So that's one.

23:41.281 --> 23:42.731
Narrator: To increase his odds,

23:42.766 --> 23:47.356
Marty targets
five more high-traffic areas.

23:47.391 --> 23:49.324
Marty:
There is a lot of wolves here.

23:49.358 --> 23:53.949
That's ideal, and the way things
are going this season,

23:53.984 --> 23:56.918
it's pretty crucial
that I take advantage

23:56.952 --> 23:59.714
of every opportunity
that presents itself

23:59.748 --> 24:03.890
and try and salvage
some of the season.

24:03.925 --> 24:07.066
There.

24:07.100 --> 24:08.792
I think I'm set up pretty good.

24:08.826 --> 24:10.725
Now it's just a matter
of letting them soak,

24:10.759 --> 24:12.243
let the wolves come back.

24:12.278 --> 24:14.591
They usually come back
within a week or so,

24:14.625 --> 24:17.559
and we'll see if I can catch
a few of them.

24:17.594 --> 24:30.227
♪♪

24:30.261 --> 24:33.126
Narrator: Across the country,
in the Ozark Mountains,

24:33.161 --> 24:36.475
Jason Hawk is just days away
from a food crisis

24:36.509 --> 24:38.856
and on the trail of the remedy.

24:38.891 --> 24:42.515
He's tracking the feral hog that
escaped his trap in the hopes

24:42.550 --> 24:44.828
that it will lead
back to the group.

24:44.862 --> 24:46.623
Jason: Well, there seems to be
some clear sign here.

24:46.657 --> 24:50.350
We're getting close.

24:50.385 --> 24:52.076
Narrator: Jason has
chased the hog's trail

24:52.111 --> 24:55.183
through the soft underbrush
for more than two miles,

24:55.217 --> 24:58.773
but up ahead, the landscape
is harder to read.

24:58.807 --> 25:00.533
Jason: These tracks
look like they're heading

25:00.568 --> 25:03.191
into some pretty rocky terrain.

25:03.225 --> 25:05.918
We got some sign
down in through here,

25:05.952 --> 25:09.059
but kind of weird
where he's heading.

25:09.093 --> 25:11.061
Tracking over leaves
is one thing.

25:11.095 --> 25:14.374
Trying to track across stone,
it's not the easiest.

25:14.409 --> 25:16.100
I've come up here a little bit.

25:16.135 --> 25:18.309
It's opened up into
a little vista,

25:18.344 --> 25:22.451
and I'm not seeing
any more tracks.

25:22.486 --> 25:24.971
I don't know.

25:27.284 --> 25:28.803
Pigs are pigs.
They go where they want.

25:28.837 --> 25:30.149
They do what they want.

25:30.183 --> 25:33.428
They just kind of wander around
wherever the food is.

25:33.462 --> 25:35.257
Narrator:
Feral hogs are omnivores,

25:35.292 --> 25:40.297
subsisting on grasses,
roots, and even rotting flesh,

25:40.331 --> 25:41.574
but they are especially known

25:41.609 --> 25:45.854
to feed on the fruit
of forest trees like acorns.

25:45.889 --> 25:52.067
Jason: Rooting around
down in through here?

25:52.102 --> 25:54.173
Ah.

25:54.207 --> 25:57.210
This is one of the reasons that
we're here in the first place,

25:57.245 --> 25:59.765
getting a bunch of nuts.

26:02.802 --> 26:06.116
This is definitely
his trail right here.

26:06.150 --> 26:08.152
I don't know how far
this pig could be.

26:08.187 --> 26:12.881
He might be 800 yards ahead.
He might be 2 miles.

26:16.540 --> 26:18.162
♪♪

26:18.197 --> 26:24.997
I got pig sign, and...

26:25.031 --> 26:27.033
yep, wild garlic.

26:27.068 --> 26:29.933
Narrator: The ancient Greeks
and Chinese first domesticated

26:29.967 --> 26:32.280
the garlic plant
thousands of years ago,

26:32.314 --> 26:36.698
but its wild relative grows
abundantly in the Ozarks.

26:36.733 --> 26:38.182
Jason: It's not
a bad little harvest,

26:38.217 --> 26:43.463
and that would go great
with wild pig.

26:43.498 --> 26:46.397
It'll make Mary happier than if
I didn't bring home anything,

26:46.432 --> 26:50.712
so that's why they call it
hunter-gatherer

26:50.747 --> 26:52.507
and not just hunter.

26:52.541 --> 26:57.408
Pick up what you can
along the way.

26:57.443 --> 26:59.997
Make use of it.

27:00.032 --> 27:03.276
Just a couple calories
at a time adds up.

27:03.311 --> 27:08.972
♪♪

27:09.006 --> 27:12.320
Now, let's figure out
where that pig went.

27:15.081 --> 27:16.738
I pushed out this far.

27:16.773 --> 27:20.500
I've got to make
this worthwhile.

27:20.535 --> 27:21.985
You just got to keep going.

27:22.019 --> 27:24.021
Your mind starts to wonder
if you've been running around

27:24.056 --> 27:26.299
like this chasing
after something.

27:26.334 --> 27:31.235
I'm thinking of pork chops,
pork roast, bacon.

27:31.270 --> 27:37.276
♪♪

27:37.310 --> 27:44.939
That's a damn pig!

27:44.973 --> 27:48.183
Stay back.

27:48.218 --> 27:51.359
Last thing I want to do
at this point is spook this pig.

27:51.393 --> 27:54.396
They don't see too well,
but they smell really good.

27:54.431 --> 28:09.170
♪♪

28:09.204 --> 28:11.275
Get that head around.

28:11.310 --> 28:13.174
[ Gun clicks ]

28:13.208 --> 28:15.555
[Bleep]

28:18.041 --> 28:20.629
[ Gunshot ]

28:22.839 --> 28:37.405
♪♪

28:37.439 --> 28:40.788
[ Sighs ]

28:40.822 --> 28:43.791
Good girl.

28:43.825 --> 28:47.587
♪♪

28:47.622 --> 28:49.866
Thank you.

28:49.900 --> 28:51.453
That's a good-looking pig.

28:51.488 --> 28:55.734
Nice, clean shot,
back of the head.

28:55.768 --> 29:00.324
Stinks to high heaven,
but he'll be good eating.

29:00.359 --> 29:01.981
I think the girls will be happy.

29:02.016 --> 29:06.537
It's just, everything else
going the way it is,

29:06.572 --> 29:09.817
it's just nice to win one
every now and then.

29:09.851 --> 29:11.197
Next thing I got to do here

29:11.232 --> 29:13.648
is start getting
this critter gutted out.

29:13.682 --> 29:16.513
Narrator: Gutting a hog on site
keeps the meat from spoiling

29:16.547 --> 29:22.174
and sheds excess weight for his
two-mile trek back to camp.

29:22.208 --> 29:23.520
Jason: Pig is over 100 pounds.

29:23.554 --> 29:25.280
It ought to last
for a couple weeks.

29:25.315 --> 29:28.318
This is the closest we get
to having a full fridge.

29:28.352 --> 29:30.113
♪♪

29:30.147 --> 29:32.391
[ Grunts ]

29:32.425 --> 29:34.324
♪♪

29:34.358 --> 29:37.361
One heavy little bastard.
He's more than 100 pounds.

29:37.396 --> 29:39.605
Get him to balance on this.

29:39.639 --> 29:41.952
[ Groans ]

29:41.987 --> 29:47.406
♪♪

29:47.440 --> 29:49.822
It's going to feel really good
walking back into camp

29:49.857 --> 29:52.721
with this pig, seeing my
little girl's eyes light up.

29:52.756 --> 29:54.378
Mary will be happy.

29:54.413 --> 29:57.381
Nothing more excites them
than fresh meat on the table.

30:00.660 --> 30:07.840
♪♪

30:07.875 --> 30:09.704
Narrator:
In the far frigid north,

30:09.738 --> 30:12.086
in the shadow
of the Great Alaska Range,

30:12.120 --> 30:15.572
the mid-winter snows are 3 feet
deep and counting,

30:15.606 --> 30:17.712
conditions that will last
until the thaw,

30:17.746 --> 30:20.335
more than two months away.

30:20.370 --> 30:23.891
To help navigate the terrain,
Morgan is undertaking a project

30:23.925 --> 30:26.755
that requires precision
and skill.

30:26.790 --> 30:31.657
Making a set of skis
is a three-stage process.

30:31.691 --> 30:33.590
Narrator:
He's hand-carving a pair of skis

30:33.624 --> 30:36.524
from freshly
harvested wooden planks.

30:36.558 --> 30:41.046
So I'm hatcheting this plank
into a rough board

30:41.080 --> 30:43.151
that I can then use
the drawknife on,

30:43.186 --> 30:45.705
clean it up
a little bit further.

30:45.740 --> 30:49.157
That's the edge
that does all the work.

30:49.192 --> 30:52.057
Narrator: First, he must whittle
the boards down to size,

30:52.091 --> 30:53.852
a thickness of less
than an inch,

30:53.886 --> 30:55.301
and then carefully taper

30:55.336 --> 30:57.717
and bend the wood
to shape the tips,

30:57.752 --> 31:01.445
the most critical element
of the ergonomic design.

31:01.480 --> 31:03.206
Morgan:
If the tips don't curve upwards,

31:03.240 --> 31:05.346
the ski is going to want
to catch in the snow

31:05.380 --> 31:09.695
and dive into the snow
instead of rising up to the top.

31:09.729 --> 31:13.630
I think this is probably
how most flat boards got made

31:13.664 --> 31:17.151
when the only steel someone
had was a knife and an ax.

31:17.185 --> 31:20.568
All right.
Well, that's a start.

31:20.602 --> 31:24.020
Let me get the other one
cleaned up, too.

31:24.054 --> 31:26.401
Narrator: Skis must be
a perfectly balanced pair

31:26.436 --> 31:28.887
to work properly,
so Morgan must ensure

31:28.921 --> 31:31.096
both are the same
length and thickness.

31:31.130 --> 31:33.650
Morgan: That's the narrowest
point on this one,

31:33.684 --> 31:35.652
and it's just wide enough
to make a ski out of,

31:35.686 --> 31:37.171
I think, just barely,

31:37.205 --> 31:41.934
as long as I don't
mess anything up too bad.

31:41.969 --> 31:43.936
I got a lot of
hatchet work to do.

31:43.971 --> 31:47.112
I'm going to be cleaning
a lot of wood off of these.

31:47.146 --> 31:49.769
I'm trying to keep them
a similar size so that

31:49.804 --> 31:54.913
when I go to plane them, they're
already close to uniform.

31:54.947 --> 31:57.846
Ah, [bleep] damn it!

31:57.881 --> 32:01.920
I knocked that thing
into my leg.

32:01.954 --> 32:04.094
Mm. I just got bit
by the corner there.

32:04.129 --> 32:06.096
Look at that.

32:06.131 --> 32:08.719
Cut.

32:08.754 --> 32:10.652
I think I'm bleeding.

32:10.687 --> 32:11.930
Oh, yeah.

32:11.964 --> 32:15.968
There's blood running
down my leg.

32:16.003 --> 32:17.142
Oh, boy.

32:17.176 --> 32:19.903
Margaret, can you get
the first aid kit out?

32:19.938 --> 32:22.043
I am cut.

32:22.078 --> 32:23.079
I can feel the...

32:23.113 --> 32:24.494
-How bad?
-I don't know.

32:24.528 --> 32:28.084
I feel blood running down
the inside of my leg, though.

32:28.118 --> 32:29.223
Hold on.

32:29.257 --> 32:32.398
See how bad it is.

32:32.433 --> 32:36.506
[ Groans ]

32:36.540 --> 32:40.855
Ooh, that's pretty bad.Yeah.

32:47.448 --> 32:49.312
O0 C1Marty: Well, no wonder
that stung pretty good.

32:49.346 --> 32:50.244
Margaret: Yeah.

32:50.278 --> 32:52.108
The corner
of the ax led in.

32:52.142 --> 32:54.558
It, like, bounced off
a wood chip and just kind of --

32:54.593 --> 32:58.493
This is the worst
cut I have...

32:58.528 --> 32:59.598
What are you
getting out of there?

32:59.632 --> 33:02.152
I'm getting the...

33:02.187 --> 33:04.189
Oh, a syringe?...diluter suture.

33:04.223 --> 33:07.986
Morgan has a pretty bad
cut there, and, you know,

33:08.020 --> 33:09.435
we're a long way
from the nearest doctor,

33:09.470 --> 33:12.300
and it has the potential
to get infected,

33:12.335 --> 33:15.165
and that would just
be a bad situation.

33:15.200 --> 33:17.064
Some iodine
right here.

33:17.098 --> 33:18.306
Narrator:
With the nearest hospital

33:18.341 --> 33:20.101
more than 200 miles away,

33:20.136 --> 33:22.552
Morgan and Margaret
must fend for themselves

33:22.586 --> 33:25.727
using their basic
first-aid supplies.

33:25.762 --> 33:27.764
An iodine solution irrigates

33:27.798 --> 33:31.319
and sterilizes
the 2-inch-deep wound.

33:31.354 --> 33:33.942
Oh [bleep] [bleep]

33:33.977 --> 33:35.013
Yeah, I'm fine.

33:35.047 --> 33:36.152
It stings
when you do that.

33:36.186 --> 33:38.533
Yeah.

33:38.568 --> 33:40.397
Trying to get a really
good look down in it

33:40.432 --> 33:42.296
to see if I can see
any tendon...

33:42.330 --> 33:44.229
Aw, damn!

33:44.263 --> 33:47.370
...or any bone or anything
because if there's a chance

33:47.404 --> 33:50.959
of any infection near a tendon
or in a ligament or bone,

33:50.994 --> 33:52.202
then that's really worrying.

33:52.237 --> 33:53.548
It could damage the joint.

33:53.583 --> 33:56.758
It could take me off
my feet for weeks.

33:56.793 --> 33:58.277
What you might want to do
is do Steri-Strips

33:58.312 --> 34:00.693
across the top
and leave the bottom section

34:00.728 --> 34:02.523
or on the bottom and the top
and leave the center.

34:02.557 --> 34:03.834
Yeah, I'm just going
to do two of them.

34:03.869 --> 34:05.767
Narrator: Steri-Strips
bind the skin together

34:05.802 --> 34:08.046
and will speed up
the healing process,

34:08.080 --> 34:11.221
but keeping the area clean
and well covered is critical

34:11.256 --> 34:13.051
to preventing infection.

34:13.085 --> 34:17.089
Put a loose gauze pad here
and change it pretty soon.

34:17.124 --> 34:18.711
Morgan: If this gets infected,
it's going to be

34:18.746 --> 34:20.299
a big blow to our schedule.

34:20.334 --> 34:22.646
For everybody's sake,
I got to take as good care

34:22.681 --> 34:24.993
of this wound
as I can, keep it clean,

34:25.028 --> 34:27.996
and hopefully,
it heals up well.

34:28.031 --> 34:29.791
Yeah, no hiking
for a few days.

34:29.826 --> 34:32.104
I'll be on
wood duty today.

34:32.139 --> 34:34.658
Being so isolated means
that even, you know,

34:34.693 --> 34:37.799
small dangers are
actually big dangers.

34:41.009 --> 34:48.707
♪♪

34:48.741 --> 34:51.641
Narrator: In Montana,
Tom closes in on home

34:51.675 --> 34:53.643
after a snow-machine breakdown,

34:53.677 --> 34:56.887
but trudging through the deep
snow in bitter cold has turned

34:56.922 --> 34:59.890
a mile-long hike into
a three-hour journey.

34:59.925 --> 35:02.272
Tom: This isn't the first time
I've walked home

35:02.307 --> 35:03.446
from my snowmobile.

35:03.480 --> 35:04.861
I'll tell you that.

35:04.895 --> 35:07.035
When they're working good,
they're a good thing

35:07.070 --> 35:09.314
to have on your side,
but sometimes,

35:09.348 --> 35:12.489
things like this happen
where they just quit on you.

35:12.524 --> 35:15.113
Narrator: But there's one
benefit to Tom's unexpected

35:15.147 --> 35:17.736
tour of his property --

35:17.770 --> 35:20.842
a chance to assess
the predator danger.

35:20.877 --> 35:22.706
Tom: I don't see any wolf sign.

35:22.741 --> 35:24.812
Everything, I think,
has just moved out of here,

35:24.846 --> 35:26.538
including the wolves.

35:26.572 --> 35:27.815
If there's nothing
for them to eat,

35:27.849 --> 35:30.507
they're not going
to hang around.

35:30.542 --> 35:33.407
What's that over there?

35:33.441 --> 35:36.237
Something alive
up there on the hill.

35:42.416 --> 35:44.072
O0 C1All of a sudden,
I see something,

35:44.107 --> 35:46.489
and my heart is beating.

35:46.523 --> 35:49.492
There's something alive
up there on the hill.

35:54.013 --> 35:55.567
It's my dog!

35:55.601 --> 35:56.844
Ellie!

35:56.878 --> 35:58.397
[ Whistles ] Ellie!

35:58.432 --> 36:00.434
Ellie, come!

36:00.468 --> 36:02.884
What are you doing
out here, huh?

36:02.919 --> 36:03.989
Come here.

36:04.023 --> 36:07.095
Come here, Ellie.

36:07.130 --> 36:09.305
Come here, Ellie!
Hi!

36:09.339 --> 36:10.858
Come, Ellie.
Come here.

36:10.892 --> 36:14.689
What are you doing?
What are you doing?

36:14.724 --> 36:17.347
I'm getting close to the house.

36:17.382 --> 36:21.248
Looks like she's chasing
a bird or something.

36:21.282 --> 36:24.596
Nance?

36:24.630 --> 36:29.048
There she is.

36:29.083 --> 36:32.155
Fancy seeing you guys
out here in the woods!

36:32.190 --> 36:33.398
Nancy: Hey!

36:33.432 --> 36:35.641
My snowmobile broke down.

36:35.676 --> 36:37.471
I've been walking
for a couple hours.

36:37.505 --> 36:40.094
Oh, no.
I'm sorry.

36:40.128 --> 36:41.371
I'm sorry, too.

36:41.406 --> 36:43.511
Well, you were at least
on your way home.

36:43.546 --> 36:46.342
Mm-hmm, yeah.
And I got the traps pulled.

36:46.376 --> 36:48.965
They were under
that much snow.

36:48.999 --> 36:49.931
They would
have never fired.

36:49.966 --> 36:51.243
No.
Oh, boy.

36:51.278 --> 36:52.900
Yeah.
That's the way it is.

36:52.934 --> 36:54.246
Can't catch them all,
can you?

36:54.281 --> 36:55.247
No.
I haven't seen

36:55.282 --> 36:56.455
any wolf tracks,
so apparently,

36:56.490 --> 36:59.355
they're all out of this area,
at least for now.

36:59.389 --> 37:00.804
For now.
Yeah.

37:00.839 --> 37:03.117
Yeah, well, you won't want
to leave that machine

37:03.151 --> 37:04.360
sit out there too long.

37:04.394 --> 37:06.638
Who knows what kind
of weather will come?

37:06.672 --> 37:08.260
Well, should we
head on back to the house?

37:08.295 --> 37:09.641
Yeah.

37:09.675 --> 37:11.608
Tom: Kind of neat to
run into Nancy out here.

37:11.643 --> 37:13.300
Come on, Ell!

37:13.334 --> 37:17.442
At least I have somebody
to walk home with now.

37:20.376 --> 37:28.280
♪♪

37:28.315 --> 37:30.282
Narrator: In the Ozarks,

37:30.317 --> 37:33.423
Jason comes home
with a 100-pound prize.

37:33.458 --> 37:38.325
After a trek like this,
it's good to see the girls.

37:38.359 --> 37:41.259
Look who I found!

37:41.293 --> 37:42.605
Look at you!

37:42.639 --> 37:44.158
Piggy pig!

37:44.192 --> 37:45.435
Jason returns.

37:45.470 --> 37:47.817
He's got a hog,
and it's awesome!

37:47.851 --> 37:49.853
You going to get
the bag, ladies?

37:49.888 --> 37:51.683
That's a good-sized one.

37:51.717 --> 37:53.098
Yes, it is.

37:53.132 --> 37:54.410
Come on!

37:54.444 --> 37:55.997
[ Grunts ]

37:56.032 --> 37:57.309
Here, let me help.

37:57.344 --> 37:58.655
[ Laughter ]

37:58.690 --> 37:59.622
I got it.

37:59.656 --> 38:01.313
-That was good.
-Good job, River.

38:01.348 --> 38:03.073
Hang on.

38:03.108 --> 38:05.628
Narrator: Without refrigeration,
Jason and Mary must work

38:05.662 --> 38:10.046
to preserve
every part of the kill.

38:10.080 --> 38:12.704
First thing I've got to do
is start breaking down this pig,

38:12.738 --> 38:19.297
which means skinning
the pig out...

38:19.331 --> 38:21.575
breaking down
the hindquarters...

38:21.609 --> 38:23.439
First piece of meat done.

38:23.473 --> 38:26.821
...front quarters, loins,
you're removing the ribs,

38:26.856 --> 38:28.098
getting everything prepared,

38:28.133 --> 38:31.619
and all of that that comes off
has to be chopped,

38:31.654 --> 38:36.037
tended, cut up,
and ready to preserve.

38:36.072 --> 38:37.522
Going to break them
down, are you?

38:37.556 --> 38:40.352
No, I'm going to
toss them in whole.

38:40.387 --> 38:42.492
Narrator: Two separate
methods of preservation

38:42.527 --> 38:45.564
will help conserve
as much meat as possible.

38:45.599 --> 38:48.153
Mary: We're going to throw
all of the bones in

38:48.187 --> 38:50.742
with the meat together, stewed,

38:50.776 --> 38:54.055
and then I'm going
to be canning that.

38:54.090 --> 38:56.264
The second thing that Mary
is getting ready to do

38:56.299 --> 38:58.301
is she's going to do
some salt pork,

38:58.336 --> 39:00.545
which will keep quite a while.

39:00.579 --> 39:03.686
We'll cut the pork butts up,
lay it in the salt,

39:03.720 --> 39:07.379
layer it in through,
and let it cure.

39:07.414 --> 39:09.588
♪♪

39:09.623 --> 39:11.797
Narrator: Salt-curing
draws out water

39:11.832 --> 39:14.248
to inhibit
the growth of bacteria.

39:14.282 --> 39:19.702
♪♪

39:19.736 --> 39:22.394
I'll be right back.
I ain't done.

39:22.429 --> 39:25.293
I like the way
you're saying that.

39:25.328 --> 39:27.744
All right.
Got some wild garlic.

39:27.779 --> 39:30.851
Ooh.

39:30.885 --> 39:33.440
Moments like this in the
mountains, they're hard to beat.

39:33.474 --> 39:36.926
♪♪

39:36.960 --> 39:38.928
Ladies.

39:38.962 --> 39:40.447
Ooh.

39:40.481 --> 39:42.380
Nice, hard day's work enjoying
the fruits of your labor...

39:42.414 --> 39:43.726
Look at that!

39:43.760 --> 39:45.659
[ French accent ] For your
dining pleasure this evening

39:45.693 --> 39:50.318
is wild boar stewed
with the finest of spices.

39:50.353 --> 39:52.148
[ Normal accent ]...hanging out
with your family.

39:52.182 --> 39:53.632
Thank you, little piggy.

39:53.667 --> 39:55.289
Thank you,
little piggy.

39:55.323 --> 39:56.808
Mm.

39:56.842 --> 39:58.879
It is really good.
Mm.

39:58.913 --> 40:02.089
Mm.
Mm.

40:02.123 --> 40:06.680
Well,
beautiful evening.

40:06.714 --> 40:08.647
You got to enjoy
what life throws you.

40:08.682 --> 40:12.064
And when it's good,
soak it up for all it's got

40:12.099 --> 40:14.032
and lick the plate.

40:14.066 --> 40:14.929
Is there something else?

40:14.964 --> 40:18.174
Because I'm missing it.

40:18.208 --> 40:22.696
[ Birds chirping ]

40:22.730 --> 40:25.284
♪♪

40:25.319 --> 40:27.355
Narrator:
Next time on "Mountain Men"...

40:27.390 --> 40:29.116
Rich: I haven't lost
one cow this year,

40:29.150 --> 40:30.738
and I'm not going to start now.

40:30.773 --> 40:32.913
Narrator: ...the predator
hunt heats up.

40:32.947 --> 40:35.916
-Whoo-hoo!
-Morgan is down for the count.

40:35.950 --> 40:38.815
Morgan: Well, it's been 24 hours
now since I cut myself.

40:38.850 --> 40:41.439
Narrator: And on Alaska's
unforgiving coast...

40:41.473 --> 40:43.475
Man: Coming up on the point
of no return here.

40:43.510 --> 40:47.479
...one man risks everything
to reclaim his birthright.

40:47.514 --> 40:49.688
Man: I'm all in here.
I sold everything that I own.

40:49.723 --> 40:52.450
This is the only place
that's ever felt like home.
